      'LAW ENFORCEMENT ACCESS WITHOUT WARRANTS: Police agencies across the country access commercial vehicle tracking databases without warrants, circumventing the Fourth Amendment protections that the Supreme Court established in Carpenter v. United States (2018) for cell phone location data. Because the data is collected by private companies and purchased by police rather than collected directly, law enforcement argues that the third-party doctrine applies and no warrant is required. ICE has used Vigilant Solutions data to track immigrants. The DEA accesses ALPR data for drug investigations. CBP uses license plate reader data at border crossings extending 100 miles inland. At least 9,000 law enforcement agencies have access to commercial ALPR databases.',
